If we look at this history with a broad perspective, we see a trend of Christianity moving further and further away from its origin. Today's world shows a growing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people might resist new ideas, they may not be influential enough to change the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow in future years. There will be a desire to differentiate between the doctrines added to Christianity over time from Jesus' original intent. This reversal in Christian history will take decades or even centuries, but it is inevitable. A movement will grow that will peel away layers of doctrine, one after another, as if the clock were moving backward, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity remains. When this trend spreads through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if they were living during Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church will remain strong to lead the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme diversity in Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. History is filled with great reversions. For example, Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, but later, the empire became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the Christian religion, undoing history to find its source and undoing diversity in the process. This process will be made possible by a method of reading Jesus' words as metaphorical, not as literal statements. What happened since Jesus' lifetime? If we look far back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning of Christianity. Monotheism, the belief in a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at the core by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united, dividing into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I firmly believe that The Jungle demonstrates the intrinsic greed and self-centeredness of humans. At our core, we are driven to make our lives as comfortable and successful as possible, without much thought for those beneath us. This is evident in the behavior of the factory owners and managers, who prioritize their corporate interests above all else. They will stop at nothing to expand their empires, regardless of the harm caused to people or the environment. As Upton Sinclair describes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This imagery illustrates the stark disregard these industrialists have for the pollution and suffering around them, including the animal waste and toxic fumes that poison the air and soil.

The factory owners also displayed no concern for their workers' well-being. They exploited them harshly, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They forced workers to labor long hours and abruptly fired them en masse for any reason, leaving them jobless and without compensation. During the time The Jungle is set, there were few legal protections for workers, allowing the owners to operate with impunity. Employees were expected to endure the terrible conditions and accept the constant threat of job loss, with no recourse or aid.

The lack of unions or support organizations in Packingtown further exacerbated the plight of the workers. While some unions were formed, they often proved more exploitative than helpful, lining their own pockets from the workers' misfortune. This system of exploitation and oppression reduced workers to a state of near-slavery, with their lives and opportunities entirely at the mercy of the factory owners, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers employ various methods to evoke specific emotions or attitudes in their readers regarding significant subjects. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs several of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he pairs adjectives and nouns in unusual ways to create a particular atmosphere around a subject. Other times, he ascribes symbolic significance to colors, which he later uses to convey feelings about certain objects. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald imbues colors like white/gray and red/pink with meaning and uses these meanings to evoke feelings about important subjects.

Fitzgerald's association of white/gray with uniformity is particularly notable. He establishes this meaning early in the novel by frequently using these colors. Daisy and Jordan are often described as "in white" (8), and nearly everyone at Gatsby's party wears white, including Nick in "white flannels" (41), Tom in a "white shirt" (36), and Catherine as "powdered milky white" (30). The only exceptions are when Nick observes Gatsby's party, where he notices "gaudy primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald also uses white/gray to describe common or unremarkable subjects, such as the "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), the "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, and the "gray old man" (27) selling dogs. After building up these associations, Fitzgerald employs white/gray to signify uniformity or insignificance. This technique begins with Daisy, whom he describes as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster," making her seem less like a character and more like a uniform object Gatsby desires (74). Fitzgerald employs this approach with Daisy repeatedly, further emphasizing her uniformity, as seen in her "gray haze" and later in a white dress (115) before her encounter with Tom and Gatsby.

San Diego County's mild, sunny climate makes it a powerhouse in agriculture. Tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers flourish here. There's a thriving demand for organic, community-supported agriculture in the area, with many local organizations boasting long waiting lists for produce. Organic eggs and milk are also popular among locals. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching, generating additional income and educational opportunities.

Organic farming, while offering greater biodiversity and habitat improvement, comes with higher costs. It demands more intensive labor and management to control pests and weeds without chemicals. Losses can be higher, and small farms lack the economies of scale of larger operations. Non-organic practices beneficial to wildlife, like planting cover crops, strategic grazing, and invasive species removal, also come at a labor cost. Therefore, a landowner in this situation might seek financial assistance or expertise to optimize profits and habitat quality.

The chosen property is a 160-acre parcel in Potrero, San Diego County, California, featuring chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. It's part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion under the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which lists over a hundred species, many of them endangered or declining, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, certain butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher.

Native Americans inhabited this land for centuries, followed by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This land was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing and wood production. I chose this property from a real estate website, researching available government programs to help a small farmer mitigate costs and preserve wildlife-friendly operations. An organic farm in the same area serves as a model for what this land could achieve.

Culture plays a big role in any negotiation. It's not just about what culture is, but also what it isn't and what it stands for. Culture isn't uniform and isn't just national or international; it varies from place to place. Sayings like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are too broad. A better approach is to understand how a culture's attitude can affect negotiations. When meeting a foreign culture, you naturally compare it to your own, which is natural. To understand a culture, you might look at its history or its prejudices. Don't judge or try to change it; instead, work within its boundaries, especially if you're at a weaker bargaining position. If you're in a foreign environment, respecting traditions and beliefs can help overcome barriers. It's also important to remember that a culture isn't just national—many companies within a nation have their own corporate culture, which can affect dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. For example, some companies encourage philanthropy while others restrict it. Even in American culture, corporate attitudes vary widely. Some cultures may appear more uniform but are still worth digging deeper into. Values are crucial too, as they explain why a culture is the way it is. If saving face is important in a culture, you won't publicly shame your company or superior to win a negotiation. A hard-driven bargain might be more important in another culture, so not settling early is key. Understanding these cultural nuances before negotiations begins is important, but also learning about your opponent personally can make negotiations more effective.

Okay, so here's a familiar quote, "The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’" This is from Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and it's the starting point for St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. This idea is also shared by another author, Thomas Aquinas. Since we're comparing their arguments, we'll assume both are right about the existence of a god, particularly the one from the Bible. Otherwise, comparing their arguments wouldn't make sense. Now, while they both have valid points, neither really provides a complete reason to believe in this God.

Let's start with St. Anselm's basic argument. He suggests that you can find proof of God's existence within your own mind. It's all about understanding through faith. He says that since God is within our understanding, we can't doubt his existence. This is a bit wordy, but essentially, he's saying that God is proven by what we already know within our own minds. No outside evidence needed, that's what faith is all about.

Now, Thomas Aquinas takes a different approach. He believes you can prove God's existence through reason and empirical evidence, no faith required. This would be great for bringing in new converts, as they could be convinced by logic alone. He presents five different logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument shows that God's existence is a logical necessity. It's like saying, if you know you're missing one piece of a puzzle, you can figure out what it looks like without actually seeing it.

So, in short, both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas bring up good points, but neither provides a solid, complete reason to believe in God.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince known as Siddhartha Gautama was born. He later became Buddha and his teachings gave birth to Buddhism, with the most traditional branch being Theravada. The religion has been around for nearly 2500 years, growing and changing over time. You can see this evolution in places like Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. While Buddha didn't teach about such a ceremony, monks and laypeople still participate, illustrating how the religion has evolved. This evolution isn't limited to superficial practices but also extends to its core beliefs. The Theravada community has had to adapt their doctrines, influenced by both internal and external factors, both hostile and benign.

Throughout this discussion, I'll use several key terms. Internal forces refer to those from within the Buddhist community, regardless of whether they are monks or laypeople. External forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that seek to harm or damage Buddhism, driven by a negative perception. Benign forces, on the other hand, don't necessarily wish to support or harm the Buddhist community but might do so incidentally.

Before diving in, let's understand Theravada Buddhism's core principles. Buddhists take refuge in the Triple Gem—the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka sets out rules for life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these concepts is key to escaping Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and overcoming lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka provides rules for laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five precepts, while monks have many more rules to abide by. The most fundamental belief in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is Dukkha (suffering), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and there is a path to enlightenment.

The United States and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest. There were other disputes between the two nations, which persisted until the First World War. The rivalry originated from disagreements on religion, culture, and tradition, as well as differing material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).

This is similar to how many other nations have enduring rivalries with their neighbors, often driven by shared borders and conflicting interests. The U.S. and Mexico are not unique in this regard, with David M. Pletcher (1977) noting that only Mexico and Cuba have had long-lasting overarching American diplomatic issues (p. 41). These nations are geographically close to the U.S. and have historically been rivals, unlike most other Latin American countries which have maintained good relations with the U.S.

Religious differences have often been a source of tension between nations, a trend seen throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) highlights that in the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy (p.86), much like the Cold War rivalry between the U.S. and the Soviet Union, which was partly ideological and partly a competition over vital interests. However, in this case, the ideological strife was rooted in religious preferences rather than political structures. This mistrust stemmed from the historical enmity between the English and Spanish, which made establishing friendly foreign relations difficult.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes were territorial issues, involving border raids and frontier problems. Bandit and outlaw attacks from American border towns were a significant issue until both nations employed military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

The rivalry began to fade as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the U.S., and finally ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico later in the 19th century (Schmitt 1974, p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly struck down by an illness I had never known existed. I was a nurse, having chosen this profession out of a deep longing for the safety and security I hadn't experienced as a child. The mantra "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick" echoed through my adolescence and beyond. Despite dreaming of a career in science or journalism, I opted for nursing. Yet, here I am: 46 years old, single, with no financial stability and unable to work. My disability persists, and after 15 years of relying on Social Security Disability, I have little left to call my own. Each day is a struggle, a relentless assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, but one thing is clear: I couldn't have endured for all these years without the support of my family and a few trusted friends. And let me tell you, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

The lesson here is that life is filled with emergencies, both big and small. No amount of preparation can guarantee that you'll overcome everything on your own. I wholeheartedly agree that we should cease relying solely on big government. I'd much rather see Americans learn to trust one another again, to help each other and to ask for help, rather than each of us retreating to our backyards to build fallout shelters.

Conservatives in the U.S. often talk about "rugged individualism" as the force that built this country. But the truth is, our forefathers didn't cross the Rockies in wagon trains alone. It was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources that saw them through hard times.

So, do prepare. I have supplies: a disaster kit with first aid, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources for a small farm, and the ability to can or preserve food, do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment. But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there any limitations or rules that dictate how they evolve? While in 1917 D'Arcy Thompson noted that “Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms,” the same can be said today. Modern mathematical modeling has been applied to study mollusk skeletogenesis through both development and evolution, as seen in works by Raup and Stanley in 1981. Our research explores how combining mathematical modeling and experimental studies can help understand the mechanisms driving evolutionary and developmental change in Prunum. We analyzed X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative traits, which were entered into the software program CerioShell. By creating hypothetical shell morphologies, we aimed to interpret the limits of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better comprehend macroevolutionary events within this group.

Imagine a shell as a structure that spirals through 360 degrees of space over time, forming a coiled structure called a whorl. These whorls turn around an imaginary central column, known as the columella, which runs through the shell's center. The rate at which whorls grow can vary, and the line separating each whorl is called a suture. Most shells have the largest whorl as the last one, known as the body whorl. The spire includes all whorls except the last, with the apex at the top and the base at the bottom. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles: apical (top), basal (bottom), apertural (front), and abapertural (back). The usual orientation is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first view the shell from the apical side and identify where the first suture starts. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts and count whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. This movement can be traced using coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture along with horizontal and vertical radii.

This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical model is established, parameters can be varied to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

Another month has come and gone, and despite the lack of significant changes in my life, a few notable events have transpired. Indonesia's progress on reducing neonatal and infant mortality over the past decade has been lackluster, despite making strides towards meeting some Millennium Development Goals. Specifically, the target goals for child and maternal health are far from being met by the 2015 deadline. Several factors contribute to this, suggesting that the overall health system needs bolstering rather than just programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has seen improvements in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% meeting this criterion. However, this figure includes traditional workers like midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions in complicated pregnancies, leading to a high number of maternal deaths from hemorrhage. This improvement is somewhat misleading, and there's still much work to be done. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by a health professional, and the data on postnatal care is incomplete, indicating a concerning trend.

Cesarean-section rates remain below the expected level, at about 4%. Urban areas have a c-section rate of 7%, compared to just 2% in rural settings. This highlights the issue of healthcare equity, as services are primarily concentrated in urban areas. There's also a stark difference in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, with a 27% gap, pointing to difficulties for the poor in accessing healthcare services due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering how to tackle the lack of service in improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the primary question is whether Indonesia should focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system. While programmatic approaches offer targeted and manageable objectives and faster results, they can lead to funding imbalances, resource allocation issues, and duplication of services. The challenge lies in determining the most effective path forward.

Victorian literature is renowned for its meticulous detail and fixation on the aristocracy of the era. Notably, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights deviate from this norm, incorporating mystery and eccentricity to enrich the characters and their motivations.  The two novels often employ dreamlike elements to convey a sense of unease and confusion, which helps to deepen the reader's understanding of the characters' emotions and inner turmoil.

"Suddenly, a cacophony of bewildering and disorientating ideas flooded his mind. He seemed to be walking with Sikes and Crackit, who were engaged in a heated argument. Their voices echoed in his ears, as if they were happening right then. Abruptly, he realized he was speaking to them. Then, a report of gunfire echoed through the air, and a rush of lights and shouts filled his vision. He was being swiftly carried away by an unseen force. Through this flurry of images, a constant, gnawing awareness of pain lingered, tormenting him.

His experience with the shooting, revisited in Chapter 28, was revisited in a vivid dream-like state as he struggled to seek help. This passage underscores Oliver's lack of control over the events and the desperate state of his health, evident through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself numbed all his senses, and he did not even notice the 'unseen hand' that bore him away. The pain was now a constant, linked with fear rather than surprise. This experience raises questions about whose will brought about his misfortune, as it certainly wasn't his own. This shooting highlights Oliver's lack of control over his life, as he couldn't even attempt to influence the outcome, even as his life was in jeopardy, a growing sense of defeat is implied, suggesting that Old Fagin had begun to break his spirit, forcing him to accept despair and limiting his ability to react. Had Oliver not been in such a state, he might have made some effort to save himself.

'The day passed – a day? It was gone before it came, and night returned, long and silent, yet fleeting in its duration. The night was a long, dreadful silence, yet short in its passing.'"

A couple of years ago, I worked at an after-school program tutoring elementary students. I did my best to assist them with their subjects, but my strengths were in English and reading. I was asked by one of the instructors to help a young boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. He seemed to have peculiar reading issues. He could pronounce some letters perfectly while others were way off. I realized something was wrong; he was of Latino descent, yet he spoke perfect English. We struggled until I met his mother. She spoke only Spanish. With my limited Spanish skills, we communicated, and that's when it hit me: Adrian could read but didn't know the English alphabet well. I'm not sure if this revelation helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the challenges of the language barrier in schools, especially in California. Even if a child speaks perfect English, reading it can still be difficult. This problem is evident, and so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no one-size-fits-all answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—no single solution will fix this problem. The key is to combine all these approaches.

Firstly, the dual language system is a fantastic idea. It's beneficial not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all kids. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." Many fears surround this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that most children won't benefit. But this isn't true. If we implemented these programs more widely, all children would reap the benefits. How do we do this? Should all teachers be bilingual? No, that's unrealistic. However, there's no reason we can't have bilingual aides or tutors to support these programs.

Just as we grow up, many of us are told from a young age that there is something greater than ourselves, something beyond our comprehension. Some of us are introduced to this concept through Sunday school, others through Temple, or we explore it within ourselves. Some readily accept the beliefs passed down by our parents, while others reject them entirely, denying the existence of anything beyond our personal experiences. Our journey to define part of ourselves often involves spiritual exploration, searching for a guiding light to lead us out of the shadows and into the sun. “A cardinal,” my father replied when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch, listening to the rain pour down, while we smoked our cigarettes. He looked out into the rain, as if looking back in time. He had become frail, his clothes loose on his body, and his hair sparse. He gazed into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him, as it would only make it more real. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the rain fall on the June twilight. My father passed away in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemotherapy and radiation did not ease his suffering but prolonged it a few months. I could not watch him pass away, as I wanted to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news. No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel," as described by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, is essentially a blend of "Old-New," much like an oxymoron. The Gothic genre has been both criticized and celebrated, often accused of lacking depth and praised for its "terrible sublime" atmosphere (Burke). The original Gothic novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, merged the elements of both ancient and modern romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole incorporated old theatrical elements and the mimicry of nature in modern novels to present a "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre often references medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" was used to describe various cultures, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to modern societal and literary advancements. The fusion of traditional Gothic elements and the new format of the novel, allowing readers a more personal view of characters' psychology, is what has kept the Gothic genre relevant for so long, making it both obsolete and fresh to readers far removed from the original era.

A key concept in Gothic novels is the idea of Chivalry. The medieval concept of knightly training and the chivalric ideal, both retained and transformed in The Castle of Otranto, are central to Gothic literature. Chivalry was important to Gothic writers because it represented the classic knight—brave, honorable, and competent—contrasted with their perceived lack of these qualities in contemporary society. By using chivalric themes and manners, the Gothic past is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the evolution of Gothic to Romanticism and serving as a means to improve the present. Walpole, writing during a politically tumultuous time, may have felt that the supposed morality and inherent goodness of the Gothic era had been lost in society. This is evident in his characters, like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits. Before meeting Frederic, he is described as:

Supply chain management is the sequence of processes moving goods from the order point to the final delivery to the customer. The term was coined by Keith Oliver, a consultant, in 1982. He described it as the planning, implementation, and control of everything that occurs within the supply chain to satisfy customer needs quickly and efficiently. Six key elements make up a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these elements to deliver top-notch customer service.

First among these elements is production, the backbone of the supply chain. This stage lays out when, where, how, and why products will be produced. Managers must understand what customers want, which they can determine by examining the market. Once they analyze the market and grasp customer demand, they can decide which products to produce and in what quantities. After setting production targets and choosing the best facilities, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Every detail is crucial in production, as improper planning can lead to significant time and money losses. For instance, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target, where every aspect of the business had a designated process, from employee uniform design to receiving shipments. Clear, outlined processes ensure smooth operations without confusion or mismatches in expectations.

The second key element is supply, which involves strategic decisions about a facility's core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. A company might have multiple divisions for producing a single product, each with unique equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must decide which division best suits each part of the product process. They may also choose to outsource work to other companies to achieve velocity – the ability to deliver quality and flexibility while keeping costs low.

Just today, I saw a peculiar sign in the street. It read, "Hitler is alive in Burma." Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stood alone on the corner, holding a piece of cardboard with this ominous message. Burma, or Myanmar as it's also known, is a Southeast Asian country that's been under the iron grip of a tyrannical military junta since 1962, when they seized power through a coup d'état. In 2007, street protests erupted, led by Burmese monks, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. These protests, dubbed "The Saffron Revolution," initially saw peaceful gatherings but soon escalated into violent clashes between the monks and the military junta, with monasteries being ransacked and foreign journalists, including a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai, being imprisoned or even killed, like on September 27th, 2007. The official death toll stands at 13, but a defected colonel from the army suggests the real number could be in the thousands.

This isn't an isolated incident. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens. Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors were believed to be gods, and even our current president, George W. Bush, is said to consult with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a branch of the Republican Party. Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where intellectuals, workers, and students were killed in the hundreds to thousands. There was also the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups and the government systematically murdered Tutsis and political moderates, irrespective of ethnicity. And who can forget Hitler's Third Reich, where Jews were systematically rounded up and killed across several countries.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz is largely due to his endurance and his ability to mold his orchestra. His piano presence is often subtle in his compositions, but as a composer, Ellington excelled at creating intricate and deep pieces that highlighted the individual skills of his band members. Ellington crafted a framework where soloists could freely improvise and wrote tightly arranged pieces and phrases that showcased the unique style of each band member, emphasizing the overall tone of the orchestra to create consistent and original sounds for each piece. His mastery of individual players' sounds and how they complemented each other in a growing ensemble allowed him to write some of jazz history's most innovative and brilliant works. The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s use of voice as an instrument, with Creole Love Call being an early example of this. This piece uses voice to add texture and color without lyrics, and also showcases Ellington's ability to complement his soloists, a trait evident throughout his career. Creole Love Call features six choruses, each with distinct elements such as voice and reed call and response, muted trumpet solos, and full band echoes. Ellington's use of voice to add tone color is just one of his stylistic traits that permeate his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines tight orchestration with an ear for tone color. He uses a call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, with Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton playing a key role in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Another day had passed, and I'd been feeling that persistent itch again, that gnawing need for something, anything. This sensation had been a constant companion since I hit puberty, now three years strong. It started as a desire for things, but had morphed into a craving for someone. Yet, the right someone had eluded me. Boys had shown interest, but none had sparked anything within me. I'd spent years puzzling over this peculiar predicament, but it was a mystery that remained unsolved. So, I carried on with life, my mind a whirlwind of questions and curiosity.

A typical day at home was usually a peaceful symphony, with my parents as the calm conductors. They never raised their voices, and their daughter was a rare fly in the ointment. Arguments were few and far between, except for my insistence on asserting my independence. I was a likeable, nice girl, but my spirited personality was a stark contrast to my parents' calm demeanor.

Today, however, was far from that usual serenity. As I wandered from room to room, seeking inspiration for my own soul, a shriek from the kitchen pierced the air. My mother's voice echoed through the house, and I rushed to the kitchen, heart pounding. "Mom? Mom, what's wrong?!" I shouted, panic rising. My mother lay on the floor, groaning and clutching her side. "Ow... sweetie... I... need you to take me to the hospital," she managed to say, her words rushed and pained. I quickly gathered her, cradling her in my arms, and carried her to the car. That morning's leisurely walk transformed into a mad dash to the hospital.

The hospital's sterile scent filled my nostrils, but my mind was too focused on helping my mother. I rushed her to the triage, calling for assistance. A flurry of medical personnel surrounded us, taking her away to be evaluated. I was left to wait, worry gnawing at me.

Mom had fallen from a stepladder while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet in the house.

Another study has revealed that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), shown by a high "alternate Mediterranean diet score" (aMed), is linked to a lower risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as reduced stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a tweaked version of the Med diet, with more plants like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, more monounsaturated fats compared to saturated ones, and less animal products and saturated fats. Drinking alcohol in moderation is also part of the diet.

Previous research has indicated that following the Med diet lowers the risk of total and cardiovascular mortality and is better than a low-fat diet for weight loss and lowering cholesterol levels in those who are overweight. However, previous studies didn’t focus on the risk of stroke or stroke mortality.

This study observed over 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, with no prior history of heart disease or diabetes, from the Nurses' Health Study, a large cohort of nurses in 11 US states. Six times, over 20 years from 1984 to 2004, they calculated an aMed diet score based on food intake reported by the nurses. Over 95% of the nurses participated throughout the study. To ensure reliability, the reported data and health outcomes were verified by medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Body mass index (BMI), smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were also tracked, and starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To account for variations in individual food intake, an average aMed score from the repeated food frequency questionnaires was calculated. Adjustments were made for factors that could affect the results, such as age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using the Cox proportional-hazard model, the study examined the relationship between the aMed diet score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal cases.

The research found that higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of heart disease and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up, there were 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths. Women in the top aMed group had a lower risk of both heart disease and stroke compared to those in the lowest group (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America was struck by a devastating financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the housing market tanked, and some of the country’s most significant corporations were left in shambles. This recession continues to this day, so let's delve into how this happened and how we can prevent it from recurring. In essence, the financial crisis was the result of self-serving and naive political choices that compelled banks and firms to issue sub-prime loans, further stressing an already fragile and insufficient financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to back and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks found themselves short on capital reserves, passing the chaos to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and onward to the rest of the economy.

The roots of this crisis can be traced back to the Clinton era in 1999. The President was in the midst of a reelection bid, aiming to bolster his popularity by relaxing lending restrictions. This move laid the groundwork for the sub-prime crisis that would unfold seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999 that, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest mortgage underwriter, was under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income individuals and faced pressure from shareholders to maintain its remarkable profit growth.” Holmes accurately predicted the repercussions of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation could face trouble in a downturn, necessitating a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As mentioned in the introduction and foreseen by Holmes, ill-advised lending would indeed plunge the economy into crisis.

Several factors combined to send the economy spiraling, one of which was the intricate structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used in the years leading up to the crisis, further intertwining different sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led to U.S. households and financial markets becoming overly leveraged in the housing market, making them highly susceptible to even minor price fluctuations.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had purchased mortgage-backed securities in financial misery. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively held $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt by 2007, which represented about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were compelled to become commercial banks under strict regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Exposition, that's the part of your story where you stretch out your writer's wings and take flight, or perhaps you just bore your readers to tears. Dr. Merlin's been known to shout at her screen when she finds herself stuck in "Too Much Information," not in a good way.

My gentle readers know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages where nothing happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder saying, "Get the history out of the way to get to the good parts," not to be confused with the other devil urging you to tell your audience every single detail of your characters' pasts.

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose. In film, it's when a character dumps information on another, like the Ancient Mariner. In fiction, it's you doing the telling.

An example: As you read, you're told the heroine met her beloved, they married, and he died in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this to take two pages with minimal dialogue. You'd expect the author to show the husband's character through words and actions, to feel his love for her. You'd expect to see their bond grow, to understand her thoughts and dreams through his eyes, and so mourn his death with her, growing closer to her.

In short, you'd expect more substance to the story's skeleton: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. Sometimes it's tempting to rush past things. Maybe you're introducing a new character and you know he was in the Air Force, now runs a gas station, was married twice, no kids, loves fishing, secretly dreams of owning the station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I caught two news segments from Columbus, Ohio today, August 13, 2011. The first was a live broadcast from NBC 4. The main story was about a bloke named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Not much about her, but they showed his mug shot and he looked like he was straight out of a bad horror movie. They only gave it about two minutes, which seemed about right given it was still an unfolding story. The second story was about some kid named Travis Buyers, 18, who got shot in the Sharon Woods area and was in critical condition. They didn't have any arrests yet and the SWAT team was on the case. This story was a bit short, which might have been because it was a "black" man or a black neighborhood. I've noticed over the years that minorities get less coverage when they're victims of a crime. If it's a white child or adult, the media goes nuts, but minorities are lucky if they even get a mention. The next story was about finding a gunshot hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that hit the chopper. Crime-Stoppers are offering a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest. The storm updates were next; they said Saturday's afternoon would have rain and thunderstorms, with temperatures in the mid to low eighties over the weekend. They kept it brief but it was a teaser to keep you watching. They also had a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store, they emphasized his blackness and how dark he was. Another guy named Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin, was sentenced for conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts from Texas to Ohio. They strangely used "300 months" instead of "25 years" in prison. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but I don't think that was relevant to the story.

The bond between brothers is something special; a tie that cannot be easily broken. This bond is a canvas for many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers have a unique understanding of each other, a connection that goes deeper than any other relationship. This bond is most visible in times of crisis, where the true nature of their feelings for one another becomes clear, whether it is for good or for ill. The consequences of these emotions are significant, and understanding them is key to navigating this complex relationship. When one brother looks into the eyes of another, they see not just their sibling but a reflection of themselves. Their actions and the results of their actions reveal their true character. This theme is beautifully depicted in "The Scarlet Ibis", where two brothers embark on an ill-fated journey through a lush, vividly described landscape. The story is told through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which conveys the protagonist's complex feelings and his view of the world. These feelings heavily influence his actions.

The protagonist's actions are driven by a single emotion: pride. From their first outing together to their final, tragic journey, the protagonist feels a sense of resentment towards Doodle. He had envisioned a brother who could share his worldly skills, like holding breath underwater, running, jumping, or climbing trees. He wanted a brother who could join him in adventures like running to Horsehead Landing or perching in the tall pine tree behind the barn. However, Doodle's condition—an extremely weak heart—made these dreams unachievable. The protagonist's dreams were shattered, and he felt anger towards the child. He even considered smothering Doodle with a pillow to end his life. What kind of child would have such thoughts? However, his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him. This simple act of love gave him hope, showing that his conviction to harm Doodle was not strong. In the back of his mind, he still loved his brother, despite his resentment.

The human brain is a complex, innovative information processing system. Over the ages, as technology evolved from primitive to modern, so did the metaphors used to understand the brain. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and more recently, a computer. As you explore the brain, keep in mind that these metaphors, while useful, can also lead to misconceptions.

Information processing begins with sensory organs, which convert physical sensations like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. These signals are transformed by the brain's algorithms through both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing integrates simple information like color and orientation to identify it as a box. Top-down processing then supports this recognition, helping you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole.

Once information is processed, an attention filter determines its importance and directs it to the relevant cognitive processes. For example, your brain processes every blade of grass when you look at your shoes, but a healthy attention filter discards these details, allowing you to focus on your name even in a noisy room. This filtering happens at various stages.

For the brain to process information, it must first be stored. Memory exists in different forms: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is encoded based on its type, such as structurally for visual stimuli or phonemically for auditory ones. Verbal input can be encoded semantically, referring to its meaning. Once stored, information must be maintained. Working memory, which holds data for about 20 seconds, is maintained by electrical signals looping through neurons. Long-term memory is thought to be maintained by structural changes in specific proteins.

There are various models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, influenced by human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model suggests that concepts (nodes) are connected based on their relatedness. For example, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so on.

Aldous Huxley, in his novel Brave New World, takes aim at the encroaching threat of technology and the capitalist structure that reinforces it, painting a grim picture of a dystopian future. In this world, people prioritize community over individuality and are conditioned since birth to seek instant happiness above all else. The citizens are mere pawns in a larger game, confined to a single ideology imposed by the World Controller. Through a Marxist lens, Huxley's suspicions about the faults in the emerging economic system become evident. Terms like homogeny and reification highlight the societal conditioning that mirrors the faults of the capitalist system he sees around him.

Capitalism is mocked through the concept of false consciousness, where the common people are kept unaware of their true economic relations, focusing solely on personal gain. This control is evident in the conditioning of Brave New World's citizens, who are driven to consume, spend, and indulge. This is manipulated by the World Controller, a form of hegemony where lower classes are unaware of their oppression, while upper classes, like the Alphas and Betas, mostly accept their designated roles. The interactions between different classes are significant indicators of the perceived oppression of capitalism.

Brave New World presents a society where individual relationships are superficial and lack depth. Characters are indistinguishable from one another, suggesting that technology and capitalism strip people of their free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent; interactions are kept shallow, with men focusing on women's physical attributes and women discussing their encounters without shame. This complacency with one's social status is a reflection of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are convinced of their superiority as long as they consume and conform to societal norms.

So another semester has gone by, and here I am, still trudging along at University Park. It's been two and a half years since I started here, or four and a half semesters. Navigating this campus can be a real pain, especially when you're stuck in the farthest reaches, like East Halls. Back in my freshman year, I was all the way east, practically at the edge of the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. A 25-minute walk to classes in the Willard building, especially in bad weather, was a real chore. I found out from an alum that not too long ago, East Halls was separated from the rest of the campus by vast empty fields. Now that space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments, and campus expansion is making it even harder to get around. So, what's the solution? Bikes, of course! But they're only useful if students use them, and the campus needs to be designed with cyclists in mind.

I was chatting with a friend who recently picked up cycling after a few years off. He said, “Bikes are great, for a few years it wasn't cool to ride, but it's the most efficient way to get around.” Plus, they're good for your body. Just a bowl of oatmeal and a little effort can take you 30 miles or more. I live off campus now, as far from the center as some dorms. The smartest move I've made this year was buying a bike. Classes at Thomas building take 25 minutes to walk, but on a bike, it cuts that down to 5 minutes if you pedal hard. The only downside is Pollock Road, the straightest route from my house to Thomas, isn't always the easiest to ride. Still, I'd rather bike than walk, as it saves me an extra 30-40 minutes every day, which adds up to over two and a half hours a week. If I didn't have a bike, walking would be my only option, and that's just not feasible with my busy schedule.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes.
