Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. It was this desire that refused to be fulfilled. It started when she was about 14, just getting into a teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she had determined she wanted someone rather than thing. Yet, she had felt no interest in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, gone through the awkward attempts to woo the un-woo-able, but no one appealed to her. She questioned herself often with this strange notion, trying to think of what it was that could possibly cause such a strange thing to happen with a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing good enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

So, I'm all set to dive into an education in social work. My dream is to work with the Division of Family and Children Services, helping kids who have been abused or neglected, and providing support for troubled families. I've got some core values that I think I can bring to the social work field: service, respect, ethical nature, and a commitment to improving relationships between people, as well as my own professional growth. These values aren't just for the job; they're deeply personal to me too.

I've always had a heart for helping others, but I wasn't sure what career path to take. Throughout high school and college, I saw many people shying away from their problems and using coping mechanisms that weren't ideal. These experiences led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took a break from my studies. One summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy nervously sitting on her couch. Turns out, he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parents’ house. I offered to help, driving over to the house to talk to the police. They asked me to talk to the parents, as there was nothing they could do legally for the teenager. The parents seemed nervous and blamed their son for involving outsiders to resolve simple disputes. After this, I started seriously considering a career in social work to help kids with family conflicts.

Another key value in social work is social justice. Our society claims to value the individual, but often we follow archaic traditions rather than truly embracing uniqueness. If we mourn lost individuals, why strive to be like everyone else? I am an individual and I don't want to limit myself based on what others are doing. Throughout my years in high school and college, I stood up against social injustice in many ways: unnatural hair colors, unique clothing choices, ear piercings, involvement with GSBA, fighting against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will continue to protest injustices I see.

So here's a quick rundown of what the paper's all about. It's a deep dive into Biological and Sociocultural models and their take on insomnia. The Biological model zeros in on the genetic and health aspects, like how genes and medical conditions can mess with sleep. Meanwhile, the Sociocultural model looks at environmental factors, including race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review takes a closer look at insomnia through these lenses, breaking down each piece of research to explain how it relates to these models. It also critiques the strengths and weaknesses of these studies.

Sleep disorders come in all shapes and sizes. You've got primary sleep disorders like dyssomnias or parasomnias, which are standalone issues. Sleep disorders tied to another mental disorder usually fall under Axis I or Axis II disorders, which cover things like clinical and personality disorders. There's also sleep disorders linked to medical complications or substance intake. Let's break down the dyssomnias a bit: Primary Insomnia is when you can't get enough sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia is when you can't stay awake. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. Parasomnias, on the other hand, are behavioral and physical issues that happen during sleep, like Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The review focuses on insomnia, and it dabbles a bit in primary sleep disorders in general.

Now, the Biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, inherited traits, and physiological factors. Neurons in the hypothalamus, which produce orexin, play a crucial role in regulating sleep and wakefulness. A study on mice found that GABAB receptors on these neurons control sleep-wake states. When these receptors are activated, they promote sleep, and if they're not firing correctly, it can cause reduced anxiety and sleep disturbances. A GABAB agonist, baclofen, extended sleep time in the study (Matsuki et al., 2009). This suggests that what's happening in mice can be similar in humans, showing a genetic and environmental basis for sleep disorders. If there's a problem with these receptors, it could impact sleep without medication, affecting life aspects like school, career, and routine tasks.

This paper delves into three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD): a brief definition, diagnosis, and strategies for teachers in mainstream classrooms to assist students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) is essentially a breakdown in the brain's ability to process sounds we hear. In other words, people with CAPD can hear normally, but their brain struggles to translate and understand sounds, particularly in noisy environments or when distinguishing between words. This disorder is often referred to as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) and was first identified in the mid-1950s, when researchers termed it "auditory imperception." The journey to understanding CAPD includes pivotal contributions from researchers like Kimura and a national conference in 1977.

Symptoms of CAPD vary but can include difficulty hearing sounds in space, distinguishing between sounds, recognizing sound patterns, and detecting changes in speech. People with CAPD might also struggle with sound synthesis, where they can't interpret sounds meaningfully, and may have trouble determining the sequence of auditory information.

Diagnosis involves thorough screening by professionals like audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. Tests range from simple questionnaires to advanced acoustic signal recordings. It's important to note that there's no single, foolproof test or known cause for CAPD.

To support a student with CAPD in a mainstream classroom, teachers can adopt various strategies. These might include reducing background noise, clearly enunciating instructions, and providing visual aids. Encouraging the student to face the teacher or use assistive listening devices can also help. The key is to create an environment that minimizes auditory distractions and maximizes understanding.

So what do you think about Shakespeare's Twelfth Night and the whole business of disguise? Well, it seems that while dressing up as someone else might be useful for pulling off a long con, in the end, you've got to shed that disguise or risk losing yourself. But watch out, 'cause when you finally come clean, you might find yourself all alone, cut off from the people you care about. After all, some folks might just take it in stride, but others, well, they might not be too happy about being fooled. And let's talk about gender swap deception, 'cause that's got its own set of issues. So why do people feel the need to hide behind a disguise? Take Viola for example. She's new in town, so she decides to masquerade as a man to keep herself safe. Her plan works, but it also makes her feel alienated from other women, and to top it all off, Olivia ends up falling in love with her. And don't even get me started on the whole Viola-Cesario-Orsino thing. It's like Viola is trapped in this love triangle, and she's the only one who doesn't know what's going on. You'd think that Shakespeare was trying to show us how deception can help release hidden emotions, but when you dig deeper, it's like Olivia is just judging people based on what they look like. I mean, she goes from being smitten with Cesario to acting like Viola is her sister. It's like she can't make up her mind. So yeah, deception can have some weird effects on people, but at the end of the day, it's all about choices. Do you risk losing yourself, or do you risk losing the people you care about?

German colonial rule has been widely noted for its harshness, particularly the genocide committed against the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. However, it's crucial to remember that nothing as vast as a colonial empire can be explained through a single description. The German colonial empire was as diverse in its policies and ruling styles as it was in its geography. Educational provision across the colonies varied greatly. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a significant population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also commended by contemporary authors. The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast. Unlike in East Africa, where the government played a major role in educating the locals, in South West Africa, native education was largely left to missionary societies that received minimal government support. The government did, however, invest heavily in educating Europeans, establishing a system of state schools and providing significant support to missionary schools. These educational policies had lasting impacts on South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies boasted substantial numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this divergent experience. This paper seeks to delve deeper into these factors and focus on new research regarding the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. There is a substantial body of literature on education within the German colonial empire, with many of these sources written in German and dating from the early 20th century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. Early works primarily aimed to describe the educational systems in these colonies, while later works expanded this discourse through comparative studies and more detailed analyses of specific educational aspects. These studies highlighted significant differences across the colonies' educational systems. Cohen’s study on education in South West Africa and East Africa is particularly notable. Cohen compared the educational systems of both colonies and discussed the factors contributing to the differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounted for many of the colony’s educational system's distinctive features. Compared to other German colonial possessions, South West Africa had a climate that was generally more temperate, with large portions covered by arid desert. This moderated climate attracted a relatively substantial European population. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population, had only 5,336 whites.

So, over the past 100 years, the classification of pop music has expanded to include countless genres, making it a challenge to list them all. To make matters more complex, most, if not all genres like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres. Within this vast landscape, the sub-genre of heavy metal rock has proven to be one of the most diverse and expressive, with a history of innovation dating back 40 years.

Today, heavy metal has evolved into a genre with countless niches, making it difficult to define what it truly is. It has absorbed themes and influences from numerous other genres, but it all started somewhere. To comprehend the heavy metal music prevalent today, one must first grasp the essence of the metal movement and why it is more than just a genre.

Metal, in many ways, is defined by its darkness. It's often dubbed a "music of more" – more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. It's less primitive and more skilled, with metal bands often showcasing exceptional instrumental prowess. Additionally, metal is heavily associated with drug use. The psychedelic drug boom of the mid-70s led to the creation of some of the genre's most iconic, otherworldly records. This drug influence has also been a significant factor in the movement's dark, visceral qualities, which were somewhat novel in the context of popular music at the time. Furthermore, later generations have drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral elements of the Romantic Era, as seen in lyrics like these from Helter Skelter by The Beatles:

These lyrics demonstrate the darker side of The Beatles, exhibiting an up-and-down rhythm that some attribute to drug use. This song is often considered one of the first heavy metal tracks, serving as a response to a heavier, darker Rolling Stones song. The Beatles aimed to prove they could be as heavy as the Stones, resulting in this iconic track on The White Album.

Once upon a time, long before the Surrealist artists painted their dreamlike masterpieces, there was Henri Rousseau, an artist who literally and figuratively crafted his own dreams. The Dream, a 1910 piece by the Post-Impressionist artist, isn't just about a woman in awe of her dreamt land; it's a reflection of Rousseau's personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. He dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, but faced a tough internal struggle: should he conform to or mimic certain painting styles to gain acceptance, or forge his own unique path?

Before diving into The Dream, let's explore Rousseau's life story. Born in Laval, northwest France, on May 21, 1844, he was the son of a tinsmith and hardware dealer. He grew up without formal art training and worked as a gabelou (municipal toll employee) until he was 40. After his first wife, Clémence, and eight of their infant children passed away, Rousseau was left with his daughter Julia and immense grief. Painting became his escape and fresh start. Unlike his contemporaries who idealized peasants in their art, Rousseau was a folk painter, dreaming of the average class's hopes and dreams.

Rousseau's desire for art world acceptance is understandable in context. Uneducated in art, he started painting late and worked alongside other accomplished artists. Recognition came to him when Matisse was gaining traction. According to Jan Gordon in Modern French Painters, both artists were different: Matisse feared painting tritely, while Rousseau dreamed of a conventional picture that would gain him entry into the Artiste Français.

Many a great thinker has suggested a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe this is because, at the core of it, there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats puts it in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why something is beautiful or moral, rather than a set of rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

More to the point, criticism of art or morals can never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. For instance, a conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa may discuss foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not explain why it is good art. Typically, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, we often hear, “There's just something about it” before a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals cannot be fully reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O’Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how well we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is always something intangible that is left unsaid. I believe the same is true for ethics. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.

I believe morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenal level, using a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, such as music, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Germany, as we know it today, is a robust and unified nation, a living tapestry of cultures that stretch from the majestic peaks of the Alps in München to the Baltic shores of Kiel. This unique cultural blend can be felt from the bustling streets of Köln on the Rhine, through the heart of Germany, all the way to the elegant city of Dresden, nestled along the Elbe. Given this diversity, it's no surprise that Germany's identity has been shaped by various sources and tribes.

The land of the Germans was once known as Germania. The origins of its name are hotly debated among scholars. Tacitus, a Roman historian, suggested the name came from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought against the Gauls. Julius Caesar, in his accounts of the Gallic Wars, used the term "Germanus" to distinguish between the conquered Gauls and the Germanic tribes who often crossed the Rhine for warfare. The exact origin is uncertain, with some proposing it could come from the German spear, known as a ger, or from the Old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," indicating that the Germans were loud or noisy.

Early Roman historian Tacitus wrote in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum" that he believed the Germans were aboriginal, having not mixed with other races through immigration or contact. He wondered, who would leave the fertile lands of Asia or Africa to settle in Germany, with its harsh climate, rugged landscape, and stern people? The Romans, for their part, did not initially settle in Germania. They sent expeditions to trade with the Germanic tribes and occasionally led military campaigns, but they mostly returned to their sprawling empire. As Germanic tribes began emerging in the first century, they lived on the fringes of the Roman Empire, trading goods and skills with the Romans, and even serving in their army.

I was staring down, my mind completely blank, trying to take in the view in front of me. Unemotionally, I studied the object, but I couldn't relate it to any deeper understanding. My thoughts were flowing in and out of my mind, so rapidly that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own. I was just experiencing the view as it was.

Once, on the advice of an artist I worked with, I bought a drawing book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had always wanted to learn how to draw since I was six, and this book teaches everything from understanding the pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is to frame any picture you want to study in a square. This way, a complex picture, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen, becomes simpler and more manageable.

But when I looked at the bowl of fruit in front of me, I couldn't mentally frame it. I was so overwhelmed and awestruck that I could only stare in wonderment. Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, and Renaissance masters used a rainbow of colors. If I had any artistic aspirations, then the bowl of fruit before me was the beginning of my art, the start of my story, "Work in Brown."

My fingers touched the brush, my muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through the air. I was giving shape and form to my thoughts, perhaps the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away and disappeared. My hand hit the toilet handle again, my muscles tensing and jerking more anxiously the second time. The clogged brown package refused to budge, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.

With a mop in hand, I stood, feet apart, a green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat. I frowned, staring at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for the cleaning crew at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more introspective moments, then my hand reached for the sheet of toilet paper, wrapping it like an oven mitt. Standing up, bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother preparing the Thanksgiving turkey...

Another devastating reality we face is the alarming number of teenagers dying in car accidents. Multiple factors combine to create this deadly scenario for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that the teen brain is not yet equipped to handle the dangers of driving, exacerbated by the lack of experience. This inexperience leads to more fatal accidents, vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens fare even worse when they're behind the wheel with their peers, and studies confirm that the presence of passengers increases the likelihood of accidents.

To address this problem, states have implemented temporary provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, these measures are insufficient. The core issue is that, as a group, teens simply aren't ready to handle the risks and responsibilities of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. He found that teens under 19-20 often crave the thrill of risk-taking, which makes it sensible to delay driving until these tendencies stabilize. Continuing to award licenses to young teens will likely result in more deadly accidents and a steep rise in the death toll among teen drivers in the coming years, especially as the Baby-Boomer’s babies become eligible to drive by 2010.

Legislation to tackle this issue could be simple yet effective. Driver's education classes could continue in schools to start the learning process, but no one under 18 should operate a motor vehicle. Provisional permits could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, with a set number of practical training hours required. The number of hours could be based on current state requirements, like California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of supervised practice. To protect teens across the nation, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be sensible and effective.

The proposed legislation is not a groundbreaking idea, but a practical step towards reducing the number of teen driving fatalities.

So I decided to dive into the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, specifically the trick films from 1895 to 1901. There were fifteen in total. I spent my time describing the poetic elements of most of these trick films and examining the unique characteristics of a few from the later years.

Most trick films from the turn of the century were confined to a stage, composed within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement. They used long and medium shots, adhering to the rule of one shot equaling one film. However, some films at the beginning of the twentieth century dared to deviate from these guidelines by introducing elements like multiple shots.

One common trait among these trick films was their filming in an interior set within a frontal proscenium. The camera remained stationary, rooted in its position, not moving to follow figures or objects. This style was deeply rooted in theatre and vaudeville traditions. As a result, characters in these films mainly moved side-to-side, never walking towards or away from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move horizontally across the frame, but the camera never tracks them.

This proscenium style also leads to long and medium shots being the norm, with close-ups being almost non-existent. This aligns with theatre and vaudeville practices, where audiences would see the entire performance at once, framed by the stage's borders. Characters, therefore, generally stayed in the middle ground and did not move towards the camera, making close-ups uncommon.

Most early trick films followed the pattern of one conceptual shot per film. This constraint limited the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limited their dramatic or narrative potential; most focused on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts, with little story. However, it’s important to note that in these films, a single conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes might not equate to a single physical shot. A single “shot” could actually be several joined together to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance. Take The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) as an example. Upon close inspection, you can see the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor, hailing from Caroline, was a staunch and early proponent of Republicanism. Agriculture, his primary profession, and his short stint in politics made him a formidable advocate for personal liberty and government transparency. His commitment to agrarianism was the cornerstone of his views on governance, impacting his stances on sovereignty, constitutionalism, and even the judicial system.

Well, let me take a look back at Figure 17, and there it is, a steep decline in commuter log submissions during the third month of our project. That was certainly a bit of a letdown, and it's tough to pinpoint exactly why it happened. I mean, we're in New England, so it's natural that with the onset of winter, folks just aren't as inclined to commute by bicycle or on foot. Then there's the end of the fall semester, where everyone's heads are down, focusing on wrapping up schoolwork and grades. And let's not forget, December is filled with holiday cheer, which means many don't even need to come campus for weeks. Classes pick back up for the spring semester in late January, adding to the drop. But that doesn't explain February's low numbers. It's like any new project, we had a boost at the start, but then it's natural to see a decline. So, to give things a kick, we rolled out the Carpool Challenge Week in March, and that brought back the log submissions. But it's a challenge to keep that momentum going, especially when you've got holiday breaks and semester slowdowns. Then there's the fact that people are just so used to driving their cars. It's a big part of our culture. So, we had to find ways to incentivize alternative commuting. We gave out a bunch of gift certificates to local shops and services. It would've been interesting to see how bigger prizes like a bicycle or hybrid car would've boosted engagement. We stuck with the gift cards initially, but maybe if we'd announced a few bicycles in December and then a hybrid car in January, we'd have seen more participation.

So, you know what an ETF is? It's like a security that follows an index, commodity, or a bunch of assets, but trades like a stock on an exchange. It gives you the good stuff of an index fund with the perks of owning individual stocks, like selling short, buying on margin, and buying just a single share. Sounds great, right? Well, there's the downside—you have to pay a commission for every trade, just like you would with stocks.

Now, let's talk about another awesome thing about ETFs—they come in so many flavors! But here's a heads up, you gotta be smart and evaluate if these benefits really exist and how much they do. For this, we're looking at the ETF IHF and its top ten holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Let's take a peek at those top ten holdings and their percentages.

To see how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we'll calculate their contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return, using the current percentage of assets. Here's the chart:

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could give you a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, and a Beta 0.12 lower. It seems like a portfolio of just these top 10 could be a better deal.

But wait, before we get too excited, we gotta check if these two portfolios are actually different. To do this, we'll look at the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks, normalized to 100%, and see how it compares to the ETF IHF's standard deviation.

One of Edgar Allan Poe's most highly regarded works is "Dream-Land." Within this poem, Poe employs the term "Thulé," which Mabbott traces back to the Roman poet Virgil. Virgil used this term in reference to an island north of Britain, the edge of the known world in Greek times. While Virgil's use of the term is undeniable, there's a more contemporary source that's often overlooked. Poe was deeply interested in German literature.

This point is crucial because it indicates Poe's familiarity with the works of Goethe. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," draws comparisons between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe had imitated Goethe's style.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was renowned for his poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within the second part of "Faust," there's a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem tells the story of a king who, after his wife's death, becomes a heavy drinker and eventually decides to end his own life. The similarities between the King of Thule and the description in "Dream-Land" are striking, perhaps a dark reflection of Poe's own experiences with loss and alcohol. "Faust" was also adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, just one year before Poe's use of the term "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references "ultra Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but he employs the term "Thule" twice in "Dream-Land," bookending the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a dark and lonely landscape, haunted by the memory of dead friends and a world devoid of color, mirroring the state of the King of Thule after his wife's death. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into one of Goethe's creations.

Goethe was a significant author who Poe would have been familiar with, not only because of his respect for Tennyson but also due to the many reproductions of Goethe's works that were circulating at the time.

So, let me give you the lowdown on a legal scenario. Under California law, could a customer who got hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages? This hypothetical customer, let's call them Jennifer Palmer, argues that the store manager, Paul Martin, acted with malice because he was informed about the spill twice but chose to ignore it, delaying cleanup until he finished his dinner. Palmer could point to previous incidents where D&D customers had slipped and fallen, even though Martin was aware of the risk. The judge is unlikely to dismiss this claim outright because the evidence shows that Martin's actions were likely to cause harm and were intentional. However, the argument that his actions were despicable might be less convincing, given that there had been several slip-and-fall incidents in 2009, but still, Martin didn’t take appropriate actions to ensure the safety of his store. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee named Rich Wayne informed Martin about the apple spill, but Martin was on his dinner break and didn't want to deal with customer complaints. Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin about the spill at 5:15 pm, but again, no action was taken. By 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell, suffering a serious back injury. D&D is now being sued for damages, and we are considering filing a motion to partially dismiss the punitive damage claim. In California, punitive damages can be awarded for conduct involving oppression, fraud, or malice. The law defines malice as conduct that intends to cause harm or, if there's no intent, conduct that's despicable and committed with a willful disregard for others' safety. The court has characterized conduct as malicious if the defendant was aware of the dangerous consequences and deliberately failed to avoid them. So, could Palmer's case be successful? Well, it's complicated, but it's definitely not a slam dunk.

Just about four years back, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics that sparked heated debates in class was whether or not Islam is a hostile religion. I believe that this question is perhaps even more pertinent today than it was then. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I've witnessed a shift in the American media's portrayal of Islam, from a hostile view of extremists to an extreme form of tolerance. It's hard to imagine that in 2001, we could have ever seen a presidential candidate like Barak Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family, leading the conversation.

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad is quite fascinating. Based on what I know of his history, there seems to be a discrepancy between his biography and the personality I've come to understand. Before this course, I was under the impression that Muhammad forced converts to Islam. He would conquer tribes and force them to adopt the religion. However, the biography portrays him as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and even humble, who attracted people to his teachings without needing to compel them.

Moreover, there are uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. For instance, when Muhammad multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men, it's a style of writing that makes me believe the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as the humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This approach, to me, is problematic because it downplays the life and miracles of Jesus Christ. It's as if they're trying to steal and take credit for Jesus' life and personhood through Muhammad.

Additionally, there are many stories in the biography that seem to serve as proof of 'witness' or how people 'naturally' converted to Islam. However, many of these stories are told from the perspective of third parties. The author illustrates that they heard it from someone who heard it from someone else, and so on. I found this approach less convincing because, although it aimed to authenticate the stories, it made them seem more dubious.

What bothers me the most about this work is how it tries to elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, historical accounts contradict this notion of Muhammad being a gentle and humble man. I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the development of Christian thought that came after his life. If we look at this history with a broad perspective, we see a trend of Christianity moving further and further away from its origin. Today's world shows a growing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people might resist new ideas, they may not be influential enough to change the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow in future years. There will be a desire to differentiate between the doctrines added to Christianity over time from Jesus' original intent. This reversal in Christian history will take decades or even centuries, but it is inevitable. A movement will grow that will peel away layers of doctrine, one after another, as if the clock were moving backward, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity remains. When this trend spreads through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if they were living during Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church will remain strong to lead the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme diversity in Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. History is filled with great reversions. For example, Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, but later, the empire became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the Christian religion, undoing history to find its source and undoing diversity in the process. This process will be made possible by a method of reading Jesus' words as metaphorical, not as literal statements. What happened since Jesus' lifetime? If we look far back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning of Christianity. Monotheism, the belief in a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at the core by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united, dividing into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I firmly believe that The Jungle demonstrates the intrinsic greed and self-centeredness of humans. At our core, we are driven to make our lives as comfortable and successful as possible, without much thought for those beneath us. This is evident in the behavior of the factory owners and managers, who prioritize their corporate interests above all else. They will stop at nothing to expand their empires, regardless of the harm caused to people or the environment. As Upton Sinclair describes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This imagery illustrates the stark disregard these industrialists have for the pollution and suffering around them, including the animal waste and toxic fumes that poison the air and soil.

The factory owners also displayed no concern for their workers' well-being. They exploited them harshly, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They forced workers to labor long hours and abruptly fired them en masse for any reason, leaving them jobless and without compensation. During the time The Jungle is set, there were few legal protections for workers, allowing the owners to operate with impunity. Employees were expected to endure the terrible conditions and accept the constant threat of job loss, with no recourse or aid.

The lack of unions or support organizations in Packingtown further exacerbated the plight of the workers. While some unions were formed, they often proved more exploitative than helpful, lining their own pockets from the workers' misfortune. This system of exploitation and oppression reduced workers to a state of near-slavery, with their lives and opportunities entirely at the mercy of the factory owners, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers employ various methods to evoke specific emotions or attitudes in their readers regarding significant subjects. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs several of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he pairs adjectives and nouns in unusual ways to create a particular atmosphere around a subject. Other times, he ascribes symbolic significance to colors, which he later uses to convey feelings about certain objects. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald imbues colors like white/gray and red/pink with meaning and uses these meanings to evoke feelings about important subjects.

Fitzgerald's association of white/gray with uniformity is particularly notable. He establishes this meaning early in the novel by frequently using these colors. Daisy and Jordan are often described as "in white" (8), and nearly everyone at Gatsby's party wears white, including Nick in "white flannels" (41), Tom in a "white shirt" (36), and Catherine as "powdered milky white" (30). The only exceptions are when Nick observes Gatsby's party, where he notices "gaudy primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald also uses white/gray to describe common or unremarkable subjects, such as the "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), the "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, and the "gray old man" (27) selling dogs. After building up these associations, Fitzgerald employs white/gray to signify uniformity or insignificance. This technique begins with Daisy, whom he describes as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster," making her seem less like a character and more like a uniform object Gatsby desires (74). Fitzgerald employs this approach with Daisy repeatedly, further emphasizing her uniformity, as seen in her "gray haze" and later in a white dress (115) before her encounter with Tom and Gatsby.

San Diego County's mild, sunny climate makes it a powerhouse in agriculture. Tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers flourish here. There's a thriving demand for organic, community-supported agriculture in the area, with many local organizations boasting long waiting lists for produce. Organic eggs and milk are also popular among locals. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching, generating additional income and educational opportunities.

Organic farming, while offering greater biodiversity and habitat improvement, comes with higher costs. It demands more intensive labor and management to control pests and weeds without chemicals. Losses can be higher, and small farms lack the economies of scale of larger operations. Non-organic practices beneficial to wildlife, like planting cover crops, strategic grazing, and invasive species removal, also come at a labor cost. Therefore, a landowner in this situation might seek financial assistance or expertise to optimize profits and habitat quality.

The chosen property is a 160-acre parcel in Potrero, San Diego County, California, featuring chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. It's part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion under the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which lists over a hundred species, many of them endangered or declining, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, certain butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher.

Native Americans inhabited this land for centuries, followed by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This land was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing and wood production. I chose this property from a real estate website, researching available government programs to help a small farmer mitigate costs and preserve wildlife-friendly operations. An organic farm in the same area serves as a model for what this land could achieve.

Culture plays a big role in any negotiation. It's not just about what culture is, but also what it isn't and what it stands for. Culture isn't uniform and isn't just national or international; it varies from place to place. Sayings like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are too broad. A better approach is to understand how a culture's attitude can affect negotiations. When meeting a foreign culture, you naturally compare it to your own, which is natural. To understand a culture, you might look at its history or its prejudices. Don't judge or try to change it; instead, work within its boundaries, especially if you're at a weaker bargaining position. If you're in a foreign environment, respecting traditions and beliefs can help overcome barriers. It's also important to remember that a culture isn't just national—many companies within a nation have their own corporate culture, which can affect dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. For example, some companies encourage philanthropy while others restrict it. Even in American culture, corporate attitudes vary widely. Some cultures may appear more uniform but are still worth digging deeper into. Values are crucial too, as they explain why a culture is the way it is. If saving face is important in a culture, you won't publicly shame your company or superior to win a negotiation. A hard-driven bargain might be more important in another culture, so not settling early is key. Understanding these cultural nuances before negotiations begins is important, but also learning about your opponent personally can make negotiations more effective.

Okay, so here's a familiar quote, "The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’" This is from Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and it's the starting point for St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. This idea is also shared by another author, Thomas Aquinas. Since we're comparing their arguments, we'll assume both are right about the existence of a god, particularly the one from the Bible. Otherwise, comparing their arguments wouldn't make sense. Now, while they both have valid points, neither really provides a complete reason to believe in this God.

Let's start with St. Anselm's basic argument. He suggests that you can find proof of God's existence within your own mind. It's all about understanding through faith. He says that since God is within our understanding, we can't doubt his existence. This is a bit wordy, but essentially, he's saying that God is proven by what we already know within our own minds. No outside evidence needed, that's what faith is all about.

Now, Thomas Aquinas takes a different approach. He believes you can prove God's existence through reason and empirical evidence, no faith required. This would be great for bringing in new converts, as they could be convinced by logic alone. He presents five different logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument shows that God's existence is a logical necessity. It's like saying, if you know you're missing one piece of a puzzle, you can figure out what it looks like without actually seeing it.

So, in short, both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas bring up good points, but neither provides a solid, complete reason to believe in God.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince known as Siddhartha Gautama was born. He later became Buddha and his teachings gave birth to Buddhism, with the most traditional branch being Theravada. The religion has been around for nearly 2500 years, growing and changing over time. You can see this evolution in places like Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. While Buddha didn't teach about such a ceremony, monks and laypeople still participate, illustrating how the religion has evolved. This evolution isn't limited to superficial practices but also extends to its core beliefs. The Theravada community has had to adapt their doctrines, influenced by both internal and external factors, both hostile and benign.

Throughout this discussion, I'll use several key terms. Internal forces refer to those from within the Buddhist community, regardless of whether they are monks or laypeople. External forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that seek to harm or damage Buddhism, driven by a negative perception. Benign forces, on the other hand, don't necessarily wish to support or harm the Buddhist community but might do so incidentally.

Before diving in, let's understand Theravada Buddhism's core principles. Buddhists take refuge in the Triple Gem—the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka sets out rules for life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these concepts is key to escaping Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and overcoming lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka provides rules for laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five precepts, while monks have many more rules to abide by. The most fundamental belief in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is Dukkha (suffering), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and there is a path to enlightenment.

The United States and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest. There were other disputes between the two nations, which persisted until the First World War. The rivalry originated from disagreements on religion, culture, and tradition, as well as differing material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).

This is similar to how many other nations have enduring rivalries with their neighbors, often driven by shared borders and conflicting interests. The U.S. and Mexico are not unique in this regard, with David M. Pletcher (1977) noting that only Mexico and Cuba have had long-lasting overarching American diplomatic issues (p. 41). These nations are geographically close to the U.S. and have historically been rivals, unlike most other Latin American countries which have maintained good relations with the U.S.

Religious differences have often been a source of tension between nations, a trend seen throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) highlights that in the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy (p.86), much like the Cold War rivalry between the U.S. and the Soviet Union, which was partly ideological and partly a competition over vital interests. However, in this case, the ideological strife was rooted in religious preferences rather than political structures. This mistrust stemmed from the historical enmity between the English and Spanish, which made establishing friendly foreign relations difficult.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes were territorial issues, involving border raids and frontier problems.
